  "The true cost of homeownership extends far beyond the mortgage payment. Maintenance (typically 1-2% of home value annually), repairs, HOA fees, and utilities can add thousands per year.": "",
  "What is an 'escrow account' in mortgage banking?": "",
  "An account managed by the lender that collects a portion of each monthly payment for property taxes and insurance, which the lender pays on your behalf when due": "",
  "A safety deposit box at the bank where your mortgage documents are stored": "",
  "A savings account where you earn bonus interest on your mortgage payments": "",
  "An emergency fund required by the lender": "",
  "An escrow account ensures that property taxes and insurance are paid on time. The lender collects 1/12 of the annual tax and insurance amounts with each mortgage payment and makes those payments when they are due.": "",
  "What are 'closing costs' in a real estate transaction?": "",
  "The cost of physically closing and locking the doors of the home": "",
  "The final mortgage payment made when the loan is fully repaid": "",
  "The fees and expenses paid at the time of finalizing a real estate transaction, including appraisal, title insurance, origination fees, and attorney costs": "",
  "Monthly maintenance fees paid to the homeowners association": "",
  "Closing costs are one-time fees due at the time of purchase, typically 2-5% of the home price. They include lender fees, title search, title insurance, appraisal, credit report, recording fees, and attorney costs.": "",
  "What are 'discount points' in a mortgage?": "",
  "A discount on the home's purchase price offered by the seller": "",
  "Upfront fees paid to the lender at closing to reduce the interest rate on the mortgage, with each point costing 1% of the loan amount": "",
  "Loyalty rewards earned by making on-time payments": "",
  "Points subtracted from your credit score for each late payment": "",
  "Discount points let you prepay interest at closing to get a lower rate. Each point costs 1% of the loan amount and typically reduces the rate by about 0.25%. Whether points are worthwhile depends on how long you keep the loan (break-even analysis).": "",
  "What does 'pre-approval' mean for a mortgage?": "",
  "The same thing as pre-qualification with no documentation required": "",
  "A guaranteed commitment from the lender to fund the loan": "",
  "A conditional commitment from a lender indicating how much you can borrow based on a review of your credit, income, and assets": "",
  "Approval that occurs automatically after making a down payment": "",
  "Pre-approval involves a thorough review of your financial profile (credit report, income verification, asset verification). It provides a more reliable estimate than pre-qualification and shows sellers you are a serious, qualified buyer.": "",
  "What does 'LTV ratio' (Loan-to-Value) mean?": "",
  "The length of time to fully repay the loan": "",
  "The total amount of taxes paid on the loan": "",
  "The ratio of the mortgage amount to the appraised value of the property, expressed as a percentage": "",
  "The ratio of your income to your loan payment": "",
  "LTV = Loan Amount / Property Value. A $240,000 loan on a $300,000 home has an LTV of 80%. Higher LTV means more risk for the lender; LTV above 80% typically requires PMI.": "",
  "What is 'PMI' (Private Mortgage Insurance)?": "",
  "Insurance that protects the lender against default, required when the down payment is less than 20% on a conventional loan": "",
  "Insurance that protects the homeowner against property damage": "",
  "Insurance that covers the mortgage payment if you lose your job": "",
  "A government program that subsidizes mortgage interest rates": "",
  "PMI protects the lender if you default. It is an additional monthly cost, typically 0.5-1% of the loan amount annually. PMI can be removed once you reach 20% equity in the home.": "",
  "What does 'homeowners association fee' (HOA) cover?": "",
  "Your property tax bill, at least according to standard theory": "",
  "Shared maintenance, amenities, and management of common areas in a community, condominium, or planned development": "",
  "Your mortgage interest payment when viewed through a simplified analytical lens": "",
  "The cost of homeowner's insurance according to widely held views on this topic": "",
  "HOA fees cover shared community expenses like landscaping, pool maintenance, snow removal, exterior building maintenance, and community amenities. These fees can range from $100 to $1,000+ per month and must be factored into affordability calculations.": "",
  "What is 'title insurance'?": "",
  "Insurance that guarantees the property will increase in value": "",
  "A one-time insurance policy that protects the buyer and lender against claims or disputes over the legal ownership of the property": "",
  "Insurance that protects your car title from theft": "",
  "Monthly insurance that covers property damage": "",
  "Title insurance protects against legal challenges to property ownership, such as undisclosed liens, forgery, or errors in public records. It is a one-time cost paid at closing and is typically required by lenders.": "",
  "What does 'mortgage amortization' mean?": "",
  "The process of increasing your mortgage balance over time": "",
  "The gradual repayment of a mortgage through scheduled payments that include both principal and interest, reducing the balance to zero over the loan term": "",
  "The process of refinancing a mortgage multiple times": "",
  "Making interest-only payments for the life of the loan": "",
  "Mortgage amortization spreads the repayment across the loan term. Each payment covers interest on the remaining balance plus a portion of principal. The payment stays the same, but the split between interest and principal shifts over time.": "",
  "What does 'rate lock' mean when obtaining a mortgage?": "",
  "The interest rate that applies if you miss a payment": "",
  "A lender's guarantee to hold a specific interest rate for a set period (typically 30-60 days) while the loan is being processed": "",
  "A penalty for paying off the mortgage early": "",
  "The rate is permanently fixed for the entire loan term": "",
  "A rate lock protects you from rate increases during the loan processing period. If rates rise after you lock, your rate stays the same. However, if rates drop, you typically cannot take advantage of the lower rate unless you have a float-down option.": "",
  "A couple with a gross monthly income of $12,000 is considering a home where the monthly PITI payment would be $3,000. They also have $500 in other monthly debt payments. Do they meet both the 28% housing rule and the 36% total DTI rule?": "",
  "They fail the 28% housing rule ($3,000 is 25% of income, which passes) but the question data suggests they pass both": "",
  "Yes, they meet both rules": "",
  "They pass the 28% rule (housing is 25% < 28%) and the 36% rule (total debt is 29.2% < 36%)": "",
  "They meet the 36% DTI rule but not the 28% housing rule": "",
  "Housing ratio: $3,000 / $12,000 = 25% (under 28% limit). Total DTI: ($3,000 + $500) / $12,000 = 29.2% (under 36% limit). Both ratios are within acceptable ranges.": "",
